Up for sale is my Nikon m-308 scope with Burris P.E.P.R. mount.  The scope is 4-16 power, one inch tube, with a 42mm objective lens. It has a BDC reticle that has has graduated hash marks that correspond to the drop of a .308 round out to 850 yards, which takes a lot of the work out of hitting targets at extended ranges. Once zeroed, simply hold on the correct hash mark and fire.
I have used the optic out to 550 yards, and found the hash marks to be accurate to that distance. Pretty nifty.
The mount is a one piece mount that gives good height and eye relief; it is cantilevered so that it can be comfortably/easily mounted on upper receivers or any other picatinny rail. The upper rings on the mount also have picatinny rails on them so additional accessories (scope levels, backup sights, etc.) can be mounted.

The optic works just fine, and is in fine condition. There is one cosmetic scratch on the finish on the side of the optic, but that is all.

Includes flip up lens caps, screw in anti-reflection device, box, and original manual and paperwork.

I am selling it because I don't shoot long range very often, and actually found that I enjoy lower magnification ranges for the type of shooting I do.

postcontent:
This is the Boberg XR45-S "The world's most powerful 45ACP pocket pistol!" It is the most accurate of the pocket 45's, too. The XR45-S is a very unique pistol, especially the feeding system and magazines. At first look, the magazine seems backwards. You push the round into the closed end of the magazine. I wondered how in the hell is the slide going to rake a round off? It doesn't! After inserting a loaded magazine, as the slide is pulled to the rear, a fork grabs the rim of the cartridge and PULLS a round out of the magazine, raises it so the slide can chamber the round. Arne Boberg probably pulled out a few hairs figuring out how to make that work! Hats off to him!! Here is a link to the video http://community.bobergarms.com/video/boberg-xr9-patentpending-feed-1 This feeding system allows for the use of a 3.75" barrel that extends over the magazine. So, you have a barrel that is .45" longer than the barrel in a SPRINGFIELD XDS 45 (3.3") in a gun that is .53" shorter in length than the XDS (6.3") vs. XR45-S (5.77").The height of the XR45-S is the same as the XDS (4.4"). The width of the XR45-S is .11" wider than the XDS. The XR45-S weighs .22oz vs. 21.5oz XDS. We are not taking anything away from the SPRINGFIELD XDS, they are an excellent firearm. We are trying to illustrate that you can have equal to or better accuracy and more muzzle energy in a smaller package. That is where the XR45-S shines. This little jewel is a work of art. The slide action is smooth and slick. The stainless steel slide is machined to perfection and the tough 7075-T6 Aircraft-Grade Aluminum Frame keeps the weight down to 22 ounces. The XR45-S is +P rated and also rated to fire the powerful 45 SUPER, so you can shoot +P ammo all day long. The XR45-S can handle it and with the low bore axis and forward grip, so can you! Recoil, not a problem. I'll list a few specs and let you get to bidding. Caliber: 45acp, 45acp +P, 45 SUPER. Capacity: 6+1. Length: 5.77". Height: 4.4". GRIP Width: 1.01". Barrel Length: 3.75". title: For Sale:  Savage Mark II GXP .22LR OUTSTANDING Condition with new Nikon ProStaff 4-12x40mm BDC scope!!!
postcontent:
This is an amazing combo of an amazing rifle with an amazing scope for an amazing value.

The rifle is a Savage Mark II .22LR bolt-action rifle.  It has a beautiful wooden stock with a gorgeous color and finish, great checkering, And sling studs.  It is known as a "GXP" model - the G denotes the wood finish and the XP denotes it was a combo package with included scope.  The actual rifle is absolutely amazing - if you do not know about Savage, they are known as some of the most accurate production rifles in the country and the best overall accuracy for price you can get.  Their quality-to-price ratio is simply unsurpassed.  This rifle shoots any single .22LR ammo you feed it (via detachable 10 round magazines, included) and has a degree of accuracy nearly unbelievable in a store-bought, production rifle of this price range.

The rifle can with some cheap scope that I immediately replaced with a top-quality Nikon ProStaff 4-12x40mm scope - simply amazing.  Nikon is basically the equivalent of Savage in the optics world - they give you the highest quality-to-price ratio with unsurpassed engineering, amazing optical technology and glass quality, fully multi-coated optics and a huge 4-12x zoom range.  With the 40mm lens size you are gaining something like 98% light transmission - unreal.  I have 3 total Nikon ProStaffs and an absolutely amazing Nikon Monarch ... they are simply the best for the least money.

The rifle comes with several 10-rd spare magazines, a camo-pattern Field and Stream sling with the swivels, and the Nikon ProStaff scope mounted.  It has probably been fired somewhere from 250-500rds.  Nearly all were high quality CCI Mini Mags, CCI Standard Velocity, Federal AutoMatch, and some Federal Value Pack 36gr HPs.

I love this rifle- I am simply attempting to fund a present for my Dad and I have several other .22LR rifles I can keep shooting while using this money to buy my Dad something he wants.

** Look I hate to sell this but i have to sell something, and as I said in a previous post, I have a surplus of combat shotguns and .22LR rifles.  So those are the things I can spare the most, thus the sale.  I hate to let this go as the accuracy is absolutely *amazing* and Savage rimfire reliability is pretty legendary ... combined with the Nikon ProStaff 4-12x40mm BDC scope etc. it's just a sweet sweet shooter package.  $500 takes it.
